'''René Héctor Émile Chazal''' was a French colonial administrator. He served as [[List of colonial governors of Mauritania|lieutenant governor of Mauritania]] from 21 November 1929 to 19 June 1931.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mauritania|url=http://rulers.org/rulm1.html#Mauritania|website=Rulers.org|accessdate=September 30, 2016}}</ref> French soldier and former governor of Mauritania [[Henri Gaden]] sharply criticized Chazal's appointment, writing, "Chauzal knows nothing about Mauritania, nor the Moors, nor about any other populations of this type.<ref>Dilley, p. 381</ref> While governor, Chazal imprisoned spiritual leader [[Yacouba Sylla (religious figure)|Yacouba Sylla]], whom he considered a great threat.<ref>Hanretta 2009, p. 78</ref> It is likely that Chazal was dismissed as lieutenant governor due to a pamphlet by [[Louis Hunkanrin]] that sharply criticized his approach to slavery.<ref>McDougall 1989, p. 293</ref>

